{"phase":"product","ticketId":"21","id":"21-113","outcome":{"note":{}},"detail":"---\n\n# Product Investigation Report — Issue #21: Swift repos get fabricated grades\n\n## Executive summary\n\n**The issue is confirmed end-to-end.** Every Swift file in a certified repo gets a fabricated grade derived from git history + line counts only — no real code-quality signal. The report card looks real (Overall C, ~80%) but is hollow: 213 Swift units all get identical scores regardless of actual code quality. Five interconnected bugs and gaps drive this, spanning discovery, evidence collection, scoring, policy, and reporting.\n\n---\n\n## Finding 1: Discovery — Swift is invisible to language detection\n\n**Files:** `internal\/discovery\/detect.go`, `internal\/discovery\/generic.go`\n\nThe `GenericScanner` (`generic.go:37`) correctly maps `.swift` → `\"swift\"` and discovers `.swift` files as file-level units. But the language-detection path (`detect.go`) has **three omissions**:\n\n| Map | Missing Swift entry | Effect |\n|---|---|---|\n| `extToLanguage` (line 24) | No `.swift` mapping | `DetectLanguages()` doesn't count Swift files |\n| `configToLanguages` (line 36) | No `Package.swift` | SwiftPM manifests not recognized |\n| `languageToAdapter` (line 45) | No `swift` | Would fall through to `\"generic\"` |\n\nResult: `certify init` won't list Swift in detected languages, `certify scan` won't show it. But the GenericScanner still discovers the files — they just flow through silently.\n\n---\n\n## Finding 2: Scoring — `complexity: 0` is scored as excellent\n\n**Files:** `internal\/engine\/scorer.go:109–124`, `internal\/evidence\/metrics.go`\n\n`ComputeMetrics()` (metrics.go) always sets `Complexity: 0` — it only counts lines and comments, never computes complexity. `ComputeSymbolMetrics()` (complexity.go) only works for Go — it uses `go\/parser`. So **every non-Go file** has `complexity: 0`.\n\nIn `scoreFromMetrics` (scorer.go:110):\n```go\ncomplexity := metricOrSummaryInt(e, \"complexity\", \"complexity\")\nif complexity >= 0 {           \/\/ <— this is the bug\n    switch {\n    case complexity <= 5:      \/\/ complexity=0 hits this → 0.95\n        setMax(scores, domain.DimMaintainability, 0.95)\n```\nThe check `>= 0` treats \"unmeasured\" (0) identically to \"measured and excellent.\" For Swift, this means every unit gets maintainability = 0.95 — regardless of a 200-line SwiftUI view's true complexity.\n\n---\n\n## Finding 3: Policy violations introduce the 0.5 defaults\n\n**Files:** `internal\/policy\/evaluator.go:83–95`, `internal\/engine\/scorer.go:51–59`, `cmd\/certify\/init_cmd.go:711`\n\nThe `swiftStandardPolicy` template has two rules at severity `error`:\n- `lint-clean`: metric `lint_errors`, threshold 0\n- `test-pass`: metric `test_failures`, threshold 0\n\nThere is no SwiftLint collector (zero `swiftlint` references in `internal\/`). So `extractMetric` returns -1, and `evaluateRule` returns a violation: \"missing evidence for metric lint_errors.\"\n\nIn `Score()` (scorer.go:51–59), violations introduce dimensions:\n```go\nscores[v.Dimension] = max(0, 0.80 - severityPenalty(v.Severity))\n\/\/ severity:error → penalty 0.30 → correctness = 0.50\n```\n\nThis is why **correctness=0.5 and testability=0.5** appear in every Swift record. It contradicts the `Score()` doc comment: \"Dimensions without evidence are absent — they don't dilute the average.\"\n\n---\n\n## Finding 4: No Swift evidence collectors whatsoever\n\n**Files:** `internal\/evidence\/executor.go`, `internal\/analysis\/analyzer.go`\n\nEvidence collectors only exist for four languages:\n\n| Language | Lint | Test | Structural (analyzer) | Deep analysis |\n|---|---|---|---|---|\n| Go | `go vet`, `golangci-lint` | `go test` | `GoAnalyzer` (go\/types) | `DeepGoAnalyzer` |\n| TypeScript | `eslint` | `jest\/vitest` | `TSAnalyzer` (tree-sitter) | — |\n| Python | `ruff` | `pytest` | `PythonAnalyzer` (tree-sitter) | — |\n| Rust | `cargo clippy` | `cargo test` | `RustAnalyzer` (tree-sitter) | — |\n| **Swift** | **none** | **none** | **none** | **none** |\n\n`analysis.ForLanguage(\"swift\")` returns `nil` — no analyzer registered. `CollectAll()` has no Swift branch. The `collectStructuralEvidence()` method silently returns when no analyzer exists.\n\n---\n\n## Finding 5: `doctor` stays green for unanalyzed languages\n\n**Files:** `internal\/doctor\/doctor.go:checkAnalysisTiers()`, `internal\/analysis\/lsp_config.go`\n\n`checkAnalysisTiers()` only checks Go (always Tier 2) + LSP servers for TS\/Python\/Rust. There's no check for languages that have **neither** an analyzer nor an LSP server. Swift is invisible to doctor — it reports all-green even when the primary language (213 units) has zero analysis coverage. (Companion issue #22.)\n\n---\n\n## The exact score calculation for a Swift unit\n\nEvidence collected:\n1. `EvidenceKindMetrics` → complexity=0, code_lines=N, comment_lines, blank_lines\n2. `EvidenceKindGitHistory` → author_count, commit_count\n3. (If Swift policy loaded) Policy violations → \"missing evidence\" × 2\n\nDimensions computed:\n| Dimension | Value | Source |\n|---|---|---|\n| maintainability | **0.95** | complexity=0 ≤ 5 |\n| readability | **0.75–0.95** | code_lines (the only variation) |\n| change_risk | **0.95** | author_count ≥ 3 (git) |\n| operational_quality | **0.95** | commit_count > 50 (git) |\n| correctness | **0.50** | violation: missing lint_errors |\n| testability | **0.50** | violation: missing test_failures |\n\nWeighted average of 6 dimensions: ~0.79 → **Grade C** (for every single file).\n\n---\n\n## Scope of affected languages\n\nThis is not only Swift. Every language in `certifiableExts` that lacks an analyzer + tool collector is affected:\n- **Swift** (`.swift`) — confirmed, this issue\n- **Ruby** (`.rb`) — no analyzer, no tools in executor\n- **Java\/Kotlin** (`.java`, `.kt`) — no analyzer, no tools (though module roots recognized)\n- **C\/C++** (`.c`, `.h`, `.cpp`, `.hpp`) — no analyzer, no tools\n- **C#** (`.cs`) — no analyzer, no tools\n- **PHP** (`.php`) — no analyzer, no tools\n- **Elixir\/Erlang** (`.ex`, `.exs`, `.erl`) — no analyzer, no tools\n- **Scala** (`.scala`) — no analyzer, no tools\n- **Lua** (`.lua`) — no analyzer, no tools\n- **R** (`.r`) — no analyzer, no tools\n- **Zig** (`.zig`) — no analyzer, no tools\n- **SQL** (`.sql`) — no analyzer, no tools\n- **Protobuf** (`.proto`) — no analyzer, no tools\n- **Shell** (`.sh`, `.bash`) — no analyzer, no tools\n\nAll would get the same fabricated scoring pattern. Only Go, TS\/JS, Python, and Rust have real tiers.\n\n---\n\n## Recommended fix priorities (for the architect)\n\n**P0 — Safety:**\n1. Fix `complexity >= 0` → should be `complexity > 0` or don't emit the metric when unmeasured\n2. Mark units with no analysis tier as unsupported (grade N\/A, exclude from aggregates, surface banner)\n\n**P1 — Correctness:**\n3. Reconcile the 0.5 default: either don't create violations for missing evidence when no collector exists, or change the contract\n\n**P2 — Features:**\n4. Add a real Swift tier (tree-sitter-swift or SwiftSyntax)\n5. Wire SwiftLint collector or remove the dead template rule\n\n**Cross-cutting:**\n6. Sync `detect.go`'s maps with `generic.go`'s `certifiableExts` (fix the `.swift` omission + all others)\n7. Doctor should warn when the primary language has no analysis tier","at":805821569.083778}
